        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe the hot spot 3C 445 South with ALMA in
continuum mode and full polarization in band 3 with the aim of
studying the particle acceleration mechanisms and the topology of the magnetic field across the hot spot structure. The observation 
will be centred at the representative sky frequency of
102.5 GHz, with a total bandwidth of 7.5 GHz. At this frequency we
estimate a peak flux density of 10 mJy/beam by extrapolating the
flux from radio and NIR/optical data (Orienti et al. 2012). 
In the same way we estimate the flux density arising from the diffuse emission (inclusive of the SC component) which accounts for 2 mJy. With a sensitivity of 0.01 mJy we will be able to detect polarization from the diffuse emission with a fractional polarization level of about 1%, i.e. adequate to discriminate between the two scenarios proposed to explain the particle
acceleration on kpc-scale and to describe the topology of the magnetic field. Based on the Sensitivity Calculator
provided in the ALMA Observing Tool (cycle 2) we estimate an
on-source observing time of 1.85 hours to reach the requested sensitivity. This value is obtained assuming 34 12-m antennas, a bandwidth of 7.5 GHz, and precipitable water vapour of 5.186 mm (7th octile). The total time spent on calibrators (comprehensive of amplitude, phase, bandpass, and polarization calibrators) and overheads is 59.65 min and 50.63 min, respectively. This implies a total observing time of 3.69 h, adequate for the parallactic angle coverage. The target source extends on an angular scale of about 6 arcsecond, i.e. smaller than 1/3 of the primary beam (Field of View = 60 arcsecond) at the representative frequency, enabling the study in full polarization mode.
Since we aim at determining the spatial distribution of the magnetic
field, we request a resolution of 0.5 arcsecond, i.e. comparable to
the resolution achieved in our previous radio (VLA A-array), and
NIR/optical (VLT) images. The requested resolution is larger than the best resolution achievable by ALMA at this frequency (about 0.4 arcsecond). Although the structure is extended and complex, there are no extremely bright components that may limit the dynamic range. By means of the ALMA Observation Support Tool we simulated an image of the hot spot region using as a source model the VLT B-band image, and the observing parameters explained before, that is: a peak flux density of 10 mJy, a resolution of 0.5 arcsecond, central frequency of 102.5 GHz, a bandwidth of 7.5 GHz, a single pointing, an on-source time of 1.85 h, and the 7th octile as atmospheric condition. The simulated image indicates that the uv-coverage is adequate to image to diffuse emission and to reach our goal (Fig. 3 in the Science Justification). </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
